[1] Cholera - Mozambique (Zambezia Province)
Date: Thu 5 Nov 2015
Source: Star Africa [edited]
http://en.starafrica.com/news/fresh-cholera-outbreak-hits-central-mozambique.html


A fresh outbreak of the water-borne disease cholera has hit Mocuba, the 2nd largest city in Mozambique's Central Province of Zambezia, with 137 suspected cases, according to the provincial heath director, Idayat Cassimo. Cassimo told a meeting of the provincial government on Thu 5 Nov 2015 that samples collected from 10 patients suffering from severe diarrhea had confirmed the presence of the bacterium _Vibrio cholerae_, which causes cholera.

According to Cassimo, the treatment center adjacent to the Mocuba Rural Hospital has hospitalized 49 cases and so far 1 person has died in connection with the outbreak. About 30 people afflicted with the disease have been reporting to the facility for treatment on a daily basis.

Cassimo also said that the neighbourhoods of Central, CFM and Toma-de-Agua, all located on the banks of the Licungo River, are the worst affected areas.

Meanwhile, health authorities in Mozambique have assured people in cholera-hit areas that they have enough stockpiles of medicines to treat 1000 cases. They said efforts to control the situation, include publicizing hygiene measures, including the purification of drinking water, necessary to prevent further transmission of cholera and other diarrheal diseases.

