[3] Cholera - Tanzania (Mwanza Region)
Date: Wed 4 Nov 2015
Source: Daily News [edited]
http://www.dailynews.co.tz/index.php/home-news/43891-wide-concern-as-cholera-hits-mwanza>


Religious leaders have been urged to educate their followers on health issues, as cholera has hit Mwanza Region, killing 18 people since early September 2015.

Acting Mwanza Regional Medical Officer, Dr James Kengia, said here yesterday, 3 Nov 2015, that beliefs in witchcraft among fishing communities have led to increased deaths reported in Ukerewe Island. "We have launched an education campaign in the region and asked religious leaders to provide spiritual guidance on the problem, as health officers ensure the affected communities are served accordingly," he said.

According to updated statistics revealed yesterday, 3 Nov 2015, apart from 18 deaths, cumulative cases have reached 317, while 274 patients have been attended and discharged.

Dr Kengia said a meeting was convened at the Regional Administrative Secretary (RAS) office on Mon 2 Nov 2015 to chart strategies of containing the communicable disease. He said more cholera cases have been reported in Ukerewe Island, particularly in Nansio and Murutungulu, while the prevalence in Irugwa Island has tremendously decreased. Another District hit by the disease is Sengerema, where many cases were reported at Kanyala village bordering Nkome Island. Other districts are still safe. "People should exercise extra care and observe health directives as much as possible.

This includes staying in hygienic environments and drinking boiled water, among other preventive measures," Dr Kengia said. In Mwanza city, 2 cholera camps have been set up at Pasiansi in Ilemela municipality and another at Butimba in Nyamagana.

[Byline: Pius Rugonzibwa]

